# Reflections on the Current AI Bubble

Today is a remarkable day. Berkshire Hathaway, one of the most prominent representatives of traditional value investing, has been pushed to the edge of the top ten largest U.S. companies by market capitalization. Meanwhile, technology companies benefiting from the AI boom continue to dominate the rankings. This does not prove that the AI bubble has reached its peak, but it is a striking symbol of how far market enthusiasm has gone.

When a new industry begins to develop, people often overestimate its short-term prospects. Investors pour enormous amounts of capital into the sector, companies invest heavily in infrastructure, and expectations rise rapidly. Some of these investments eventually create the foundation for genuine long-term growth. However, when expectations rise faster than real-world applications and profits, a bubble may form.

The dot-com boom provides a useful example. In the late 1990s, many investors believed that the Internet would transform the world. They were right about its long-term importance. Large amounts of capital flowed into Internet companies and helped build essential infrastructure for the digital economy. However, the technology had not yet been fully commercialized, and many companies had unrealistic business models. Their valuations were based more on expectations than on sustainable profits.

When the dot-com bubble burst in the early 2000s, many companies disappeared. However, the development of the Internet did not stop. Instead, the crash forced the market to distinguish between companies with real value and those supported mainly by speculation. Some businesses that survived the downturn later became highly influential global companies.

AI may follow a similar path. Its long-term potential is enormous, but this does not mean that every AI-related company deserves an extremely high valuation. At some point, market expectations may have to be corrected. If a major correction occurs, it will not necessarily represent the failure of AI. It may instead create an opportunity to identify companies with genuine technological advantages, sustainable business models, and reasonable valuations.

The difficult task is not predicting the exact day on which a bubble will burst. It is distinguishing lasting value from temporary excitement.
